  "prompt": "Does a voltmeter show RMS voltage?",
  "response": "Yes, most AC voltmeters are designed to display the **RMS (Root Mean Square)** value of the voltage.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **RMS is the equivalent DC voltage:** The RMS voltage is the value of a DC voltage that would deliver the same amount of power to a resistive load as the AC voltage. This is why it's the most useful and commonly displayed value for AC voltage.\n*   **Meter design:** AC voltmeters often use circuits that convert the AC voltage to a DC voltage proportional to the RMS value, and then display that DC value on a calibrated scale.\n*   **Calibration:** Voltmeters are calibrated to read the RMS voltage for a sinusoidal AC waveform. If the waveform is significantly non-sinusoidal, the meter reading may not be accurate.\n\n**In summary, unless otherwise specified (e.g., a peak-reading voltmeter), you can generally assume that an AC voltmeter is displaying the RMS voltage.**\n\n**Important Note:**  Some specialized voltmeters may display peak voltage or peak-to-peak voltage. These types of meters are less common for general-purpose use. Always check the meter's documentation to confirm what it is displaying.",
